			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-291529">
									

<p>Suggestions for potential "fun" reactions to SCP-808</p>
<ul>
<li>SCP-914's interpretation of "batteries" - any device that requires batteries will have a slot that says "Vita". Small mammals can be inserted into the Vita slot, where they will be incorporated into the device.</li>
<li>Communication devices, if disassembled, will have a fold-out tray inside. On this tray will be one end of an old style speaking tube (a la ships at sea). The tube will obviously continue past the bottom of the tray. Investigation shows that turning the device on opens an iris within the speaking tube. Particularly industrious experimenters may disassemble both devices and then send a wire camera through. This investigation shows that the tube is 5' long, regardless of the distance between its two ends.</li>
<li>Cameras require replenishment of the pigments they use to produce the pictures which can be strange requests ranging from crushed butterflies to samples of human melanin.</li>
<li>DVD players require light to shine directly into an optics assembly consisting of many lenses. Turns out that you can remove this assembly, and with the right light source, make a pretty badass heat ray. The exact mechanics of the energy amplification will elude investigation. It *shouldn't* work… but it does.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>And finally, I can't think of any consumer electronic item that would be big enough, but I keep having images of removing the side of a computer box to see an expanse of gears extending far past where the sides of computer are supposed to be — someone small enough, in my image, could climb inside and go for days without reaching the end… and the end isn't a side or a wall. The gears just stop at a void. It appears the entire assembly is suspended in some void, with the entrance in the center.</li>
</ul>
<p>Part of me realizes that this thing should be in vacuum, that unless the case is air tight, air from our atmosphere would leak into the voidspace… which just makes me think that, rather then blowing hot air out, the mechanistic computer lets air fall in, and uses this pressure gradient to power the thing.</p>

							</div>

								
